1 Data

1.1 Retrieval

The data for 244 properties managed by Watershed were retrieved using SQL from the database which contained 5 tables. I created the following relational schema to keep track of their relationships and to prevent querying error.

Watershed Properties relational schema for database

1.2 Data dictionary

Variable name Abbreviation in R Description
ws_property_id Watershed property ID
location Location of the property (not unique since one location ID can have multiple properties)
property_type Type of property (R1 to R16, 16 combinations of apartment/house, one/two BR, whether there is a kitchen (Y/N), and whether property is shared with owner (Y/N)itchen)
current_monthly_rent lt_monthly Current long-term rental rate (monthly rate)
percentile_10th_price p10 10th percentile of short-term rental price for similar property in similar location
percentile_90th_price p90 90th percentile of short-term rental price for similar property in similar location
sample_nightly_rent_price st_nightly Example short-term rental of similar property (nightly rate)
count nights_per_year Number of nights the property was occupied in 2015
occ_rate Occupancy rate in 2015
city City (United States)
state State
zipcode Zip code
apt_house Apartment or House type
num_bedrooms Number of bedrooms
kitchen Whether there is a kitchen (Y/N)
shared Whether property is shared with owner (Y/N)

1.3 Data cleaning and name change

The names “short-term rate (STR) rate” and “nightly rental rate” will be used interchangeably.

ws_data <- ws_data %>% 
  rename(
    p90 = percentile_90th_price,
    p10 = percentile_10th_price,
    nights_per_year = count...,
    st_nightly = sample_nightly_rent_price,
    lt_monthly = current_monthly_rent)
kable(head(ws_data))

2 Modeling

2.1 Normalizing STR rate

The relationship between short-term (ST) occupancy rate occ_rate and STR rate st_nightly is not statistically significant when ST rate is input at the original scale. We normalize the example ST rate to percentile using the 10th and 90th percentile prices of its corresponding location, then add 0.1 to ensure that the normalized data falls between 10th and 90th percentiles again. Regressing the ST occupancy rate against the normalized ST rate will give significant coefficient.

# st_nightly on original scale 
ggp1 <- ggplot(data = ws_data) +
  geom_point(aes(x = st_nightly, y = occ_rate)) +
  labs(title = "ST occupancy rate vs. STR rate (original scale)")

# normalizing STR rate
ws_data <- ws_data %>% 
  mutate(st_nightly_norm = 0.1 + 0.8 * (st_nightly - p10) / (p90 - p10))

# normalized st_nightly
ggp2 <- ggplot(data = ws_data) +
  geom_point(aes(x = st_nightly_norm, y = occ_rate)) +
  labs(title = "ST occupancy rate vs. STR rate (normalized)")

grid.arrange(ggp1, ggp2, ncol = 2) 

# lt_annual_rev = lt_monthly * 12 * 0.973
